.SH NAME
.PP
add \[en] Touch multiple files and directories
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]add\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] [\f[I]path\f[R] \&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
Recursively create multiple directories and files with a single command.
Paths ending with a directory separator character (\f[C]/\f[R],
\f[C]\[rs]\f[R]) will be treated as directories and other paths as
files.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \f[C]-h\f[R], \f[C]--help\f[R]
Print help.
.TP
.B \f[C]-v\f[R], \f[C]--version\f[R]
Print version number.
.TP
.B \f[C]-a\f[R], \f[C]--all\f[R]
Print list of created paths.
This is the default.
If used together with \f[C]--open\f[R], it will open all specified file
paths.
.TP
.B \f[C]-i\f[R], \f[C]--interactive\f[R]
Interactive mode, where each path is prompted for.
.TP
.B \f[C]-l\f[R], \f[C]--last\f[R]
Print the last created path.
If used together with \f[C]--open\f[R], it will open the last specified
path.
.TP
.B \f[C]-o\f[R], \f[C]--open\f[R]
Open printed paths with external \f[B]open\f[R] command.
.TP
.B \f[C]-q\f[R], \f[C]--quiet\f[R]
Silent mode.
.TP
.B \f[C]-r\f[R], \f[C]--relative\f[R]
Each path is relative to the previous.
.TP
.B \f[I]path\f[R]
List of filenames to touch.
Paths ending with a slash are treated as directories and other paths as
files.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B \f[C]PWD\f[R]
Is used to figure out the current working directory.
.SH FILES
.PP
Depends on external programs \f[C]bash\f[R], \f[C]cat\f[R],
\f[C]dirname\f[R], \f[C]mkdir\f[R], \f[C]open\f[R], \f[C]realpath\f[R]
and \f[C]touch\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Creates 3 directories, counting sub-directories, and 2 files:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ add example/readme.txt example/src/index.js example/test/
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Creates \f[C]example\f[R] directory and 2 files into it:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ add -r example/ 1.txt 2.txt
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Creates and opens \f[C]1.txt\f[R] and \f[C]2.txt\f[R]:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ add -o 1.txt 2.txt
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Creates two files and opens the last one:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ add -lo 1.txt 2.txt
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Piping a filename is also supported:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ echo \[dq]1.txt\[dq] | add
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
A list of paths can be read from a file:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ echo 1.txt >> filelist.txt
$ echo 2.txt >> filelist.txt
$ add < filelist.txt
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Interactive mode allows creating multiple paths one by one:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ add -i
? Path:
\f[R]
.fi
